## 1️⃣  `createRoute` – URL‑template ↔ params object

```ts
/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   1️⃣  Extract the names of the “:param” parts from a literal string.
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
type ExtractParams<T extends string> =
    //  “…/:p/…”  →  take the part after the colon, then recurse
    T extends `${infer _Before}:${infer Param}/${infer Rest}`
        ? Param | ExtractParams<`/${Rest}`>
        : //  “…/:p”  (no more slash) → take the final part
          T extends `${infer _Before}:${infer Param}`
            ? Param
            : never;

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   2️⃣  Helper that makes an *exact* object type – no missing keys,
       no extra keys.
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
type Exact<P, Shape> =
    //   P must be assignable to Shape …
    P extends Shape
        // … and must not contain keys that Shape does not have
        ? Exclude<keyof P, keyof Shape> extends never
            ? P
            : never
        : never;

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   3️⃣  The public API
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
declare function createRoute<
    T extends string,
    // every extracted param must exist in the object and be a string
    P extends Record<ExtractParams<T>, string>
>(
    path: T,
    // `Exact` guarantees that *only* those keys are present
    params: Exact<P, Record<ExtractParams<T>, string>>
): { path: T; params: P };

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   4️⃣  Example usage (the only lines that type‑check)
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
// ✅ OK – keys match the template
const ok = createRoute(
    '/users/:userId/posts/:postId',
    { userId: '123', postId: '456' }
);

// ❌ compile‑time error – `wrongParam` is not a param in the template
// const error1 = createRoute(
//     '/users/:userId',
//     { wrongParam: '123' }   // ← TypeScript error
// );

// ❌ compile‑time error – missing `postId`
// const error2 = createRoute(
//     '/users/:userId/posts/:postId',
//     { userId: '123' }        // ← TypeScript error
// );
```

**How it works**

1. `ExtractParams<'/users/:userId/posts/:postId'>` → `'userId' | 'postId'`.
2. The generic `P` is constrained to `Record<ExtractParams<T>, string>`, so every extracted name must be present.
3. `Exact` makes sure the supplied object does **not** contain any extra keys (excess‑property checking works even with a plain object literal).

